Claim Audit Reference
Use this reference when reviewing drafts, product-adjacent copy, supplement content, fitness advice, nutrition advice, or any article that could be interpreted as medical guidance.
Audit Table
Use this structure:
Claim	Risk	Evidence status	Concern	Safer wording	Source needed
Risk values:
Low: general wellness education, low harm potential.
Medium: could be misunderstood, overgeneralized, or used in place of professional advice.
High: disease, medication, pregnancy, children, mental health, acute symptoms, supplements, or regulated claims.
Red-Flag Claims
Flag and rewrite claims that:
Promise cure, prevention, reversal, detoxification, or guaranteed results.
Imply a supplement or wellness habit treats a disease.
Say a practice is safe for everyone.
Recommend stopping or replacing medical care.
Use urgency, fear, shame, or stigma to drive action.
Make weight-loss, fertility, hormone, immune, mental health, pain, or disease claims without strong evidence.
Present one study as settled consensus.
Omit contraindications, interactions, or when to seek care.
Safer Rewrite Patterns
Use:
"may support" instead of "will fix"
"can be part of a broader plan" instead of "is the solution"
"some evidence suggests" instead of "proven"
"for some people" instead of "for everyone"
"talk with a qualified professional" near higher-risk tips
"seek urgent care" for emergency symptoms
Required Safety Notes
Add safety language for:
Pregnancy or breastfeeding
Children or adolescents
Older adults
Chronic conditions
Prescription medications
Supplements and herbs
Eating disorders or restrictive dieting
Severe anxiety, depression, self-harm thoughts, or mental health crises
Chest pain, shortness of breath, fainting, severe allergic reaction, stroke symptoms, or other urgent symptoms
CTA Review
Responsible CTAs can invite readers to:
Learn more
Save a checklist
Discuss options with a qualified professional
Book a coaching or wellness consultation with scope limits
Ask their clinician about whether a tip fits their situation
Do not use CTAs that imply guaranteed improvement, medical treatment, diagnosis, or replacement of care.
